{"id":"2008.02336","submitter":"Alberto Saracco","authors":"Domenico Mucci, Alberto Saracco","title":"Weak curvatures of irregular curves in high dimension Euclidean spaces","comments":"27 pages, 1 figure, Annals of Global Analysis and Geometry (accepted,\n  2021)","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We deal with a robust notion of weak normals for a wide class of irregular\ncurves defined in Euclidean spaces of high dimension. Concerning polygonal\ncurves, the discrete normals are built up through a Gram-Schmidt procedure\napplied to consecutive oriented segments, and they naturally live in the\nprojective space associated to the Gauss hyper-sphere. By using sequences of\ninscribed polygonals with infinitesimal modulus, a relaxed notion of total\nvariation of the $j$-th normal to a generic curve is then introduced. For\nsmooth curves satisfying the Jordan system, in fact, our relaxed notion agrees\nwith the length of the smooth $j$-th normal.\n  Correspondingly, a good notion of weak $j$-th normal of irregular curves with\nfinite relaxed energy is introduced, and it turns out to be the strong limit of\nany sequence of approximating polygonals.\n  The length of our weak normal agrees with the corresponding relaxed energy,\nfor which a related integral-geometric formula is also obtained.\n  We then discuss a wider class of smooth curves for which the weak normal is\nstrictly related to the classical one, outside the inflection points.\n  Finally, starting from the first variation of the length of the weak $j$-th\nnormal, a natural notion of curvature measure is also analyzed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 5 Aug 2020 19:52:23 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 9 May 2021 05:23:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-05-11"}
